  <static seed="104" source="Contrib/PCC/BasicAlgebra/FractionArithmetic/AddingFractionsOfInches10.pg">
    <statement><p>A <m>2\times4</m> piece of lumber in your garage is <m>{34{\textstyle\frac{9}{16}}}</m> inches long. A second <m>2\times4</m> is <m>{44{\textstyle\frac{19}{32}}}</m> inches long. If you lay them end to end, what will the total length be?</p>
<p>The total length will be <fillin characters="7" name="AnSwEr0001"/> inches.</p>
</statement>
    <answer>
      <p>
        <m>79{\textstyle\frac{5}{32}}</m>
      </p>
    </answer>
    <solution><p>To find the total length in inches, we add the two lengths together.</p>
<p><m>\begin{aligned}
    {34{\textstyle\frac{9}{16}}}+{44{\textstyle\frac{19}{32}}} \amp  = 34+\frac{9}{16}+44+\frac{19}{32}\\
                \amp  = 78+\frac{9}{16}+\frac{19}{32}\\
                \amp  = 78+{1{\textstyle\frac{5}{32}}}\\
                \amp  = {79{\textstyle\frac{5}{32}}}
\end{aligned}</m></p>
<p>So the total length is <m>{79{\textstyle\frac{5}{32}}}</m> inches.</p>
</solution>
